complete

  • complete(): boolean
    • Defined in lib-common/delta.ts:88

    This method completes the delta, if number of bytes left for the last skip is the same in both initial and resultant files.

    Returns boolean

    true, if delta is set as complete, and false, if it cannot be set complete, due to mismatching byte counts.

deleteBytes

  • deleteBytes(len: number): ChangeOp
    • Defined in lib-common/delta.ts:160

    This method adds a deletion change for a given number of bytes.

    Parameters

    • len: number

    Returns ChangeOp

    a change object, with the following fields: a) op is a string === Delta.DELETE, b) ifP is a position in the initial file, c) rfP is a position in the resultant file, d) len is a number of deleted bytes.

  • insertBytes(len: number): ChangeOp
    • Defined in lib-common/delta.ts:123

    This method adds an insert change for a given number of bytes.

    Parameters

    • len: number

    Returns ChangeOp

    a change object, with the following fields: a) op is a string === Delta.INSERT, b) ifP is a position in the initial file, c) rfP is a position in the resultant file, d) len is a number of inserted bytes.

packDeltaFileHeader

  • packDeltaFileHeader(): Uint8Array
    • Defined in lib-common/delta.ts:232

    Returns Uint8Array

    Uint8Array with delta's file header. Header has the following layout: a) first 4 bytes contain total header's length, b) everything else is a json form of this delta.

Static mergeDeltas

  • mergeDeltas(id: string, d12: Delta, d23: Delta): Delta
    • Defined in lib-common/delta.ts:333

    CAUTION: This function is complex, and needs adequate testing. It has some assert statements in it, which should be removed, when proper regression testing is done.

    Parameters

    • id: string

      for a new delta

    • d12: Delta
    • d23: Delta

    Returns Delta

    new delta, which is a result of merger of two given deltas. This process merges change steps, but it does not move insertion bytes from given deltas. Therefore, instead of usual byte offset (bP), all changes have array chunks, with reference object, identifying chunks of bytes from given deltas, while array implicitly dictates order for these byte chunks.
